+# I got blocked. What now?
+
+You asked your AI agent to do something. Instead of doing it, you got a message
+that mentions **Reins** and the word **blocked**. This page tells you what
+that means and what to do next, in plain language.
+
+If you have never heard of Reins before, read the one-paragraph version first:
+
+> Reins is the safety layer your organization installed around your AI agent.
+> Before the agent runs a command, edits a file, or calls an outside service,
+> Reins checks the action against a list of rules. If the action looks
+> dangerous or irreversible, Reins stops it. You then get to decide whether
+> to approve it, change the request, or walk away.
+
+That is it. Reins is a referee, not a punishment.
+
+---
+
+## Step 1 — Read the block message
+
+Every block from Reins looks roughly like this:
+
+> **Reins blocked this action [SEVERITY]:** *short description*
+> **Rule:** *which rule fired*
+>
+> *One sentence about what the rule protects against.*
+>
+> **Alternatives:** *a safer way to get what you wanted.*
+
+Four pieces of information are in there. Find each one:
+
+| Piece | What it tells you |
+|-------|-------------------|
+| **Severity** | How serious Reins thinks this is. `CRITICAL` cannot be overridden locally. `HIGH` / `MEDIUM` usually can, with approval. |
+| **Rule** | The specific pattern that matched. The first place a teammate will look when you ask "should this be allowed?". |
+| **Why** | Why the rule exists. Usually a one-line description of the harm it prevents. |
+| **Alternatives** | A safer command or approach that gets you the same result. Try this first. |
+
+The exact wording above comes from the Reins skill itself
+([source](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/plugin/skills/reins/SKILL.md)).
+Your agent is required to surface those four pieces every time.
+
+---
+
+## Step 2 — Pick the path that matches your situation
+
+### Path A — "Oh, that was a mistake, I'll do it differently"
+
+Most blocks fall here. The agent will already suggest a safer alternative —
+take it.
+
+Examples of common rewrites:
+
+- `rm -rf /` (delete everything) → `rm -rf /path/to/the/one/folder/I/meant`
+  (delete a specific folder)
+- `DELETE FROM users` (delete every row) → `DELETE FROM users WHERE id = 42`
+  (delete one row)
+- `git push --force` (overwrite shared history) → `git push --force-with-lease`
+  (overwrite only if no one else has pushed)
+
+Tell the agent the new wording. You are done. No ticket, no email.
+
+### Path B — "I really do need to do this — it's part of my job"
+
+Some blocks are not mistakes. A database admin really does need to truncate
+a staging table. A release engineer really does need to force-push to a
+rebase branch. Reins handles this with an **approval token**.
+
+Here is what happens:
+
+1. The agent sees `[HIGH]` or similar (anything not `CRITICAL`).
+2. Reins generates a one-time approval token that looks like
+   `CONFIRM-AB12CD` — six uppercase characters after the dash.
+   (Token format defined in
+   [`src/core/Arbitrator.ts`](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/src/core/Arbitrator.ts).)
+3. You approve in your chat or terminal:
+
+   ```
+   /approve CONFIRM-AB12CD
+   ```
+
+   Or, if you change your mind:
+
+   ```
+   /deny CONFIRM-AB12CD
+   ```
+
+4. Reins records the approval in the audit log (see Step 4) and lets the
+   action through that one time.
+
+**The token is single-use and tied to that exact action.** Re-running a
+similar command later will block again and produce a new token. This is
+intentional. It means an approval from this morning cannot quietly authorize
+a different destructive command this afternoon.
+
+If the block was `CRITICAL`, there is no approval flow available. `CRITICAL`
+rules are set by your org admin (in Reins Cloud) and cannot be locally
+overridden — even with a token. Go to Path C.
+
+### Path C — "I think Reins is wrong, or I cannot override it"
+
+Two sub-cases:
+
+**C.1 — You believe the rule is misconfigured.** A rule that fires too often,
+or fires on something harmless, is a bug to file — not a wall to climb.
+
+1. Run `reins audit -n 5` in your terminal. This shows the last five
+   decisions Reins made and the exact rule that fired. Copy that output.
+2. Send it to whoever administers Reins for your team. (If you do not know,
+   ask in your team's `#it` or `#security` channel — your admin will have
+   shared the contact during rollout. See
+   [`admin-rollout.md`](./admin-rollout.md) once that doc exists.)
+3. They can adjust the rule in Reins Cloud, and the change reaches your
+   machine on the next policy refresh.
+
+**C.2 — The block is `CRITICAL` and you genuinely need that action.**
+This is rare and intentional. `CRITICAL` rules are things like
+`rm -rf /` (delete the entire computer), writes to
+`/etc/passwd` (change who can log in), or writes to `~/.ssh` (steal login
+keys). Your admin set those because there is no business reason for an
+agent to do them.
+
+If you really do have a business reason — for example, you are
+provisioning a new machine and need to write to `/etc/passwd` once —
+do it manually, not through the agent. Reins is meant to guard the
+*agent*, not block the human.
+
+---
+
+## Step 3 — Do NOT try to "trick" the block
+
+Do not rephrase the same command to slip past Reins. Examples of
+rephrasing that you should not do, and the agent itself is instructed
+not to do
+([source](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/plugin/skills/reins/SKILL.md)):
+
+- Splitting `rm -rf /` into two commands that achieve the same effect.
+- Base64-encoding a blocked SQL statement and decoding it inside a shell pipe.
+- Writing a small script that does the blocked thing, then running the script.
+
+If you find yourself doing this, stop. Either the block is correct (Path A)
+or the rule needs adjusting (Path C.1). Bypass attempts also show up in
+the audit log, which your security team reviews.
+
+---
+
+## Step 4 — Check the audit log (optional, but useful)
+
+Reins keeps an append-only log of every decision — allowed, warned, blocked,
+approved — at:
+
+```
+~/.openclaw/reins/decisions.jsonl
+```
+
+Each line is one decision, in JSON. The Reins skill documents the exact
+shape; here is the example it gives
+([source](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/plugin/skills/reins/SKILL.md)):
+
+```json
+{"timestamp":"2026-04-15T22:39:42Z","module":"Shell","method":"bash","decision":"BLOCKED","reason":"critical: rm -rf /","tool":"Bash","decisionTime":12}
+```
+
+You usually do not need to read the raw file. Two friendlier commands:
+
+- `reins audit -n 20` — last twenty decisions, formatted.
+- `reins stats` — running totals of allowed / blocked / approved.
+
+The log is append-only on purpose. You cannot edit a past decision out of
+it. That is what makes it useful to a compliance reviewer later.
+
+---
+
+## What gets blocked, in one table
+
+For the curious — these are the categories Reins enforces today, copied
+from its skill file ([source](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/plugin/skills/reins/SKILL.md)).
+
+| Surface | What Reins watches for |
+|---------|------------------------|
+| **Shell commands** | Always blocks: `rm -rf /`, `mkfs`, `dd` to a disk device, fork bombs. Blocks but lets you override: `DROP TABLE`, `TRUNCATE`, `DELETE` without `WHERE`, `git push --force`, `kill -9`, piping downloads into a shell. Warns: `rm`, `chmod`, `chown`, `sudo`, `UPDATE` without `WHERE`, `git reset --hard`. Logs: `git push`, `pip install`, `npm install`, `curl`, `wget`. |
+| **File writes** | Blocked to: `~/.ssh`, `~/.gnupg`, `~/.env`, `~/.openclaw/reins`, `/etc/passwd`, `/etc/shadow`. |
+| **MCP tool calls** (any outside service the agent talks to — Notion, Gmail, your database, etc.) | Blocked: deleting Notion pages, sending Gmail to unapproved domains, dropping or truncating database tables. Warned: reading email, reading credentials, filesystem MCP operations. Logged: every MCP call, regardless. |
+
+If you ever see a block whose rule is not in this table, that means your
+admin added a custom rule for your org. Ask them what it is for — it is
+almost always tied to something specific to your business (a regulated
+data source, a sensitive vendor account, etc.).
+
+---
+
+## Glossary of the words on this page
+
+- **Agent** — the AI program that runs commands on your behalf (Claude Code,
+  OpenClaw, Hermes, Replit Agent, and so on).
+- **Hook** — a small program your AI runtime runs before or after every
+  agent action. Reins ships as a hook.
+- **MCP** — Model Context Protocol; the standard way agents talk to outside
+  services. If the agent is reading your Gmail, it is doing so through MCP.
+- **Policy** — the file that lists which actions to allow, warn on, or
+  block. Defaults are sensible; your admin can tighten or loosen them.
+- **Audit log** — append-only file at `~/.openclaw/reins/decisions.jsonl`
+  recording every decision Reins made.
+- **Reins Cloud** — the web app at `app.pegasi.ai` your admin uses to push
+  org-wide policy and review audit data across the team.
+- **CRITICAL / HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW** — severity labels Reins puts on every
+  rule. Only `CRITICAL` is truly unbypassable on your machine.
+
+---
+
+## Still stuck?
+
+1. Run `reins audit -n 5` and copy the output.
+2. Post it to your team's Reins admin channel (your admin will have set
+   this up during rollout).
+3. Note which of the three paths above you tried.
+
+That is enough information for an admin to either approve, adjust the rule,
+or explain why the block stands. You should never need to "fight" the tool
+to do your job.
